The paper deals with communication complexity, which is a topic that falls under several sub-categories in computer science. The use of randomness in communication protocols suggests that the paper could be categorized under cs.IT (Information Theory). The study of communication complexity itself falls under cs.CC (Computational Complexity). The paper also discusses compression and agreement distillation, which are topics in cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), respectively. Finally, the use of small-set expansion and invariance principles suggests a connection to cs.LG (Machine Learning).
